5 STATE OF MAINE
6 SENATE
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 112, L.D. 246, “An Act to Establish the
10 Option of Sentencing Alternatives for Primary Caregivers”
11 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
12 following:
13 'Sec. 1. 17-A MRSA §1602, sub-§4 is enacted to read:
14 4. Class D or Class E crimes. In imposing a sentencing alternative for a Class D or
15 Class E crime pursuant to section 1502 that is contested by the parties and setting the
16 appropriate length of that term as well as any unsuspended portion of that term
17 accompanied by a period of probation or administrative release, the court shall consider all
18 relevant sentencing factors, both aggravating and mitigating, appropriate to the case.
19 Relevant sentencing factors include, but are not limited to, the character of the individual,
20 the individual's criminal history, the effect of the offense on the victim, the effect of the
21 potential sentencing alternative on those relying on the individual as a primary caregiver
22 and the protection of the public interest.
23 Sec. 2. 17-A MRSA §1602, sub-§5 is enacted to read:
24 5. Primary caregiver defined. As used in this section, "primary caregiver" means an
25 individual who has the greatest responsibility for the care of a minor, a dependent person
26 or an incapacitated adult as defined by Title 22, section 3472, subsection 10.'
27 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
28 number to read consecutively.
29 SUMMARY
3300 This amendment requires a court, in sentencing a defendant convicted of a Class D or
3311 Class E crime, to consider a sentencing alternative other than imprisonment due to the
3322 defendant's being a primary caregiver of a minor, dependent person or incapacitated adult.
3333 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
3344 (See attached)
